<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img alt width="20" height="20" src="../../../../external.html?link=http://forums.whonix.org/user_avatar/forums.whonix.org/patrick/40/17_2.png" class="avatar"> Patrick:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Local or remote attacker?</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>Only a local attacker can unlock the bootloader.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="Patrick" data-post="35" data-topic="4557">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img alt width="20" height="20" src="../../../../external.html?link=http://forums.whonix.org/user_avatar/forums.whonix.org/patrick/40/17_2.png" class="avatar"> Patrick:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Either way, there is encryption / access controls. I don’t see why in one case encryption / access controls are weaker.</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>Encryption doesn’t cover everything such as the bootloader. If you allow the attacker to unlock the bootloader without wiping user data, the attacker can just replace the bootloader with a malicious one that uploads all of your data the next time you decrypt it.</p>
<p>Encryption + verified boot is necessary for any meaningful physical security.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="Patrick" data-post="35" data-topic="4557">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
